	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Anyone ever wonder how much bandwidth would be saved if there was no advertising?<BR>
<BR>
Did Everlore think about this?  Remove the screenshots and the ads, and I'd guess you'd cut bandwidth usage 50% or more.<BR>
<BR>
When Everlore takes on ads, does anyone think that downloading that extra crap, even if it's only 1 or 2k of graphics, costs money in terms of bandwidth usage?  Are the ads really worth it?<BR>
<BR>
I've been an everlore regular since mid 1999.  I can honestly say that I have NEVER clicked on an ad here.  Absolutely none of them have ever interested me.  <BR>
<BR>
Perhaps if Everlore must have ads, someone could spend some effort finding ads that the user community is likely to be slightly interested in.  Here's a hint:<BR>
<BR>
1) Drop the spank-the-monkey ads.  <BR>
2) Nobody is interested in seeing Britney Spears or Christina Aguilera.  We all get bombarded with them enough in other media.<BR>
3) We don't need dating service ads.  Your users fall into a few groups: married and not needing a date, dating and therefore not needing a date, unable to get a date if they were the last people on earth.<BR>
3) Don't use pop-ups.  Many people, like myself, deliberately don't buy services and products from companies that advertise through pop-ups.<BR>
<BR>
Someone said that if you get everlore at work you should get to work and quit complaining. Well smart guy, I have the same problem... I travel, and when I'm on the road after hours, I use my laptop (read WORK machine) to read everlore.  When those near-soft-core ads come up, I risk disciplinary action as well.  I think it's unreasonable to carry 2 laptops around when I travel so I pretty much have to not visit Everlore when I'm on the road.<BR>
<BR>
So what ads would make people scream less?<BR>
<BR>
How about computer ads?  Job posting ads from high-tech employers?  Beer ads?  Pizza ads?  Clothing ads for men's and women's clothing (we all want to look good right)?  Ads for games?  Ads for consulting services (many players are young/middle aged adults who may find it handy)?<BR>
<BR>
A little thought being put into the advertisements will go far to generating clickthroughs and irritating the user base less.<BR>
<BR>
If the ad company that everlore uses doesn't want or cannot put up worthwhile ads, perhaps the problem isn't use of bandwidth, it's a bad sponsor...
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
